Malaysia, South Korea, Thailand, Taiwan: Asian Bonds and Currency Preview

-- B y   K h a l i d   Q a y u m
-- 
2011-04-28T22:45:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-28/malaysia-south-korea-thailand-taiwan-asian-bonds-and-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan ’s financial
markets are closed today for a national holiday.  Malaysia: The central bank will report money-supply data
for March at 5 p.m. local time. It may also release figures on
foreign investors’ holding of local-currency bonds.  The yield on the benchmark 4.16 percent note due July 2021
was at 4.06 percent. The ringgit was at 2.9665.  South Korea: Industrial production grew 11 percent in March
from a year earlier, after a 9.1 percent gain the previous month,
according to a Bloomberg survey of economists before official
data today.  The yield on  South Korea ’s 3 percent bond due December 2013
was 3.80 percent. The won was at 1,071.23 per dollar.  Thailand : The current-account surplus shrank to $2.8
billion in March from $3.8 billion the previous month, according
to the median forecast in a Bloomberg survey before a report
today.  The Bank of Thailand will release foreign-exchange reserves
data for the week ended April 22. Reserves rose 0.6 percent to
$185.8 billion the previous week.  The central bank will sell 85 billion baht ($2.8 billion)
of 15-day bills.  The yield on the 3.125 percent debt due December 2015 was
3.33 percent. The baht was at 29.92 per dollar.  Taiwan: Gross domestic product rose 5 percent in the first
quarter from a year earlier, after a gain of 6.92 percent in the
three months ended December 31, according to a Bloomberg survey
before preliminary data to be released today by the statistics
bureau.  The government will sell NT$30 billion ($1 billion) of 91-
day Treasury bills.  The yield on the 1.375 percent bond due March 2021 was 1.40
percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The  Taiwan
dollar  was at NT$28.76.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Khalid Qayum in Singapore at 
 kqayum@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
